          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>The posterior and middle layers of the thoracolumbar fascia form a closed osteofascial compartment in the lumbar region. Which muscle is enclosed within this compartment?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Quadratus lumborum</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Quadratus lumborum lies between the middle and anterior layers of the thoracolumbar fascia, not within the posterior–middle layer compartment.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Erector spinae</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The posterior layer lies behind the erector spinae (attached to the spinous processes) and the middle layer lies in front of it (attached to the transverse processes), enclosing it within a closed osteofascial compartment. A haematoma or abscess in this space directly compresses the erector spinae.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Psoas major</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Psoas major lies anterior to the anterior layer of the thoracolumbar fascia and is not within the compartment formed by the posterior and middle layers.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Transversus abdominis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Transversus abdominis is an anterolateral abdominal wall muscle. It originates from the lateral raphe where the posterior and middle layers meet, but it is not enclosed within their compartment.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The erector spinae lies within the compartment formed by the posterior and middle layers. The posterior layer attaches to the spinous processes behind it, and the middle layer attaches to the transverse processes in front. Quadratus lumborum occupies a separate space between the middle and anterior layers."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct. The erector spinae is enclosed within the osteofascial compartment formed by the posterior and middle layers. Clinical significance: any collection (haematoma, abscess) within this closed space compresses the muscle."
                }
              ],
