          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>The femoral nerve and obturator nerve both arise from L2, L3, and L4 of the lumb</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>The femoral nerve and obturator nerve both arise from L2, L3, and L4 of the lumbar plexus. Despite sharing the same root values, they supply different compartments of the thigh. Which compartments do they supply, respectively?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Anterior and medial</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The femoral nerve passes under the inguinal ligament to supply the anterior compartment (knee extensors), while the obturator nerve exits through the obturator foramen to supply the medial compartment (thigh adductors). This explains why their injuries produce very different clinical presentations despite shared root values.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Anterior and posterior</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The posterior compartment of the thigh is supplied by the sciatic nerve, which arises from the sacral plexus (L4–S3), not from the obturator nerve.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Medial and posterior</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The femoral nerve supplies the anterior compartment (not medial), and the posterior compartment receives the sciatic nerve from the sacral plexus, not the obturator nerve.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Posterior and lateral</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Neither the femoral nor the obturator nerve supplies a posterior or lateral compartment. The femoral nerve serves the anterior compartment and the obturator nerve serves the medial compartment of the thigh.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The lumbar plexus supplies the anterior and medial compartments of the thigh. The femoral nerve (L2, L3, L4) passes under the inguinal ligament to the anterior compartment, while the obturator nerve (L2, L3, L4) exits through the obturator foramen to the medial compartment."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct. The femoral nerve supplies the anterior compartment (knee extension, anterior thigh sensation) and the obturator nerve supplies the medial compartment (thigh adduction). Understanding this distribution is essential for localising nerve injuries clinically."
                }
              ],
